article.headline: Finley scores 25 in win
article.story:
DALLAS (AP) -- Playing behind five proven scorers on the Dallas Mavericks, rookie Josh Howard knows he has to make the most of whatever playing time he can get. He certainly did Saturday night, scoring a season-high 15 points and providing a much-needed spark in the second half of a 92-88 victory over the Minnesota Timberwolves that kept the Mavericks undefeated at home. Both teams were playing their fourth game in five nights, so there were plenty of tired legs. Dallas also was without Dirk Nowitzki (sprained ankle) and Danny Fortson (suspended). Howard took over late in the third quarter after Dallas was down by 12. He hit a 10-footer, 20-footer, 3-pointer and two free throws during a 22-4 spurt that put the Mavericks up by six. Howard also had three rebounds and an assist during that stretch, and his white headband seemed to be wherever the ball was throughout the comeback. "I know we have a lot of stars, so whenever I get a chance to replace them, I'm going to play hard and do what I've been doing since college," said Howard, who played four seasons at Wake Forest. Howard made six of 11 shots in 25 minutes, one shy of his most, and had seven of Dallas' season-best 60 rebounds. "We are seeing his maturity as the season goes on," coach Don Nelson said. "He has a nice, quiet confidence about his game and I really think he is going to be a good player." Kevin Garnett -- who had 28 points and 20 rebounds -- single-handedly kept the Timberwolves close, scoring eight of their last nine, including a jumper that tied it at 81 with 3:46 left. He also had a 3-pointer and two free throws in the final 27 seconds that prevented the Mavericks from sealing the victory until Steve Nash made two free throws with 2 seconds left. About the only thing Garnett didn't do, according to coach Flip Saunders, was complain enough about the way he was treated on both ends of the court. There were several angry looks on his face, but few heated words. "He gets no calls as much as he goes to the basket," Saunders said. "That's why a lot of guys complain to the refs, because they get the calls. He's just too nice." Minnesota's last possession ended when Sam Cassell fumbled an inbounds pass. When time expired, Cassell punted the ball high over the court, landing in the seats. "We can't just depend on Kevin Garnett," said Cassell, who had 18 points, seven assists and six rebounds. "I don't usually dwell on losses, but this is going to be a long flight home for me." The only day off the teams have had since Monday was Thanksgiving. The Mavs went 2-2 in that stretch, while the Wolves were 1-3. Dallas, coming off road losses at Phoenix and Denver, was obviously worn out. The Mavericks had their worst shooting game of the season (34.3 percent) and scored their fewest points at home; they had been averaging 111.4. Minnesota was at its best early, shooting 56 percent in the first half. Then Dallas went to a zone defense in the third quarter and the Timberwolves cooled off, finishing at 44 percent. "It was a big effort under the circumstances," said Nash, who had 17 points and nine rebounds. "It was a huge effort from a lot of guys and a big contribution from a rookie." Howard began the season as a backup to Michael Finley, but the two played well together in this game. Finley led the Mavericks with 25 points. He hit five 3-pointers, including one at the end of the third and another early in the fourth that brought alive a crowd of 20,089. Antawn Jamison added 14 points and a season-high 13 rebounds. Antoine Walker had eight points and 10 rebounds, and was obviously frustrated with his 4-of-18 night. He was blocked on a dunk early, missed four straight free throws in the second quarter, then buried his head in his jersey after one miss with 1:34 left. Minnesota's Michael Olowokandi, playing for the second straight night after missing three games with tendinitis in his right knee, had 10 points, seven rebounds and four blocks in 31 minutes. Latrell Sprewell had 14, although six came in the first quarter.

Game notes
Dallas joined the Lakers and Kings as the only teams that haven't lost at home; all are 9-0. ... The Timberwolves lost only their second of the last seven road games. ... Nash took a game-high nine free throws. He didn't have any the previous three games. ... Minnesota's Mark Madsen missed a third straight game with back spasms. ... Dallas' previous low at home was 95 points. ... Dallas opened the second quarter 3-of-18 and started the third 2-of-12.
